<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: GARDEN GROVE; A SWEET REWARD FOR YOUNG BICYCLE RIDERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Police officers will begin next week handing citation tickets to children 
riding their bicycles -- if they are wearing a helmet. Yes, wearing a helmet! 
</P>
<P>
 But instead of a fine, the tickets are redeemable for a cone of yogurt or a 
box of cookies at any McDonald's restaurant in Garden Grove. 
</P>
<P>
 McDonald's and the Police Department launched the reward program Wednesday to 
encourage children -- and their parents -- to observe traffic laws, including 
wearing bicycle helmets. 
</P>
<P>
 Police Officer Karl Mansfield of the city's neighborhood traffic unit said 
that rewards also will be given to children wearing a seat belt or if they are 
in a car seat when a police officer pulls over the vehicle in which they are 
riding. 
</P>
<P>
 The program is a positive way to enforce traffic laws, Mansfield said. 
</P>
<P>
 At Wednesday's program launching, Police Chief Stanley L. Knee also gave 
bicycle helmets to five Garden Grove students, compliments of an anonymous $100 
donation to the Police Department's bicycle helmet program. 
</P>
<P>
 The helmets were bought at reduced prices from Dave Coombs, owner of four 
bicycle shops, who has agreed to participate in the program. 
</P>
<P>
 In July, the police distributed flyers in local schools detailing a state law, 
which requires bicycles riders to wear helmets. Starting in January, those not 
wearing helmets may be fined $25, Mansfield said. 
</P>
<P>
 The flyers included coupons that entitle the holder to buy a bicycle helmet 
for $20, less than half of the retail price, at any of Coombs' bike shops in 
Garden Grove, Anaheim and Tustin. 
</P>
<P>
 The children who received the helmets Wednesday were Elesha Kuskie, 8, 
third-grader at Lampson Elementary School; Melissa Byram, 7, first-grader at 
Faylane Elementary; Emmanuel Urbina, 12, seventh-grader at Doig Intermediate 
School; Shilo Carter, 6, kindergarten student at Faylane Elementary, and 
Mychael Moore, 8, third-grader at Evans Elementary School. BERT ELJERA 
</P>
</TEXT>
