<HEADLINE>
<P>
AUSSIE MOTORCYCLIST DOOHAN FAVORED TO WIN U.S. GRAND PRIX 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHAV GLICK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Australian Mick Doohan, who ended one United States motorcycle winning streak 
when he clinched the world 500cc championship two weeks ago, will try to end 
another one this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
 No foreign rider has won the United States Grand Prix in five tries at Laguna 
Seca Raceway, but Doohan will be favored when Round 12 of the 14-race FIM world 
championship series is run on the 2.196-mile circuit.Eddie Lawson won in 1988, 
Wayne Rainey in 1989, '90 and '91 and John Kocinski last year. There was no 
race in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
 Doohan clinched his first world title when he won the Czech Republic GP, 
ending a streak of six U.S. champions: Lawson, 1988-89, Rainey, 1990-92 and 
Kevin Schwantz, 1993. The victory was Doohan's eighth this year. 
</P>
<P>
 Last year at Laguna Seca, the 29-year-old Australian was leading with seven 
laps to go when he fell and gave the lead to Kocinski. 
</P>
<P>
 Qualifying will start today for the 500, 250 and 125 world championship 
classes, with finals in all three on Sunday. SHAV GLICK 
</P>
</TEXT>
