</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Two familiar names from the converging entertainment-technology world have 
been named to head Gov. Pete Wilson's Information Technology Council -- 
International Creative Management Chairman Jeffrey Berg and Oracle Chief 
Executive Larry Ellison. 
</P>
<P>
 The council will work to ensure that California takes advantage of 
opportunities arising from the information revolution in areas ranging from 
education to the economy, Wilson said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
 Other entertainment and technology representatives on the 27-member council 
include Enrique Baray, senior vice president of Univision; Ronald Fortune, 
president of Viacom Inc.'s Computer Curriculum Corp., and Eddy W. Hartenstein, 
president of DirecTV Inc. 
</P>
<P>
 The council also includes Curtis Hessler, Times Mirror Co. executive vice 
president; Spencer Kaitz, president of the California Cable Television Assn.; 
Robert Kavner, a senior executive at Creative Artists Agency; Alan Kay, a 
fellow at Apple Computer; Gary Matus, executive vice president of Bank of 
America; Marc Porat, chairman of General Magic; Phil Quigley, chairman of 
Pacific Telesis, and Maggie Wilderotter, senior vice president of McGraw 
Cellular Communications Inc. 
</P>
<P>
 Twentieth Century Fox announced the resignation of Andrea Jaffe. Jaffe has 
served as president of domestic marketing since 1992. There was no reason given 
for the split. 
</P>
<P>
 Producer John Davis has signed a three-year, first-look deal at Fox. He has 
also hired David Friendly as the company's president.  
</P>
<P>
 Leslie Hinton has been named executive vice president for strategic 
development at Fox Television. 
</P>
<P>
 Tim Sarnoff is the new senior vice president of animation production 
management at Warner Bros. Animation. 
</P>
<P>
 Wayne Lepoff has been named chief executive of Genesis Entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
 Barry J. Stoddard and Theodore R. Lau have left Group W Productions to form 
MediaPoll, an entertainment research firm. 
</P>
<P>
 TriStar Pictures has named Ben Cosgrove manager of creative affairs, Andrea 
Giannetti a reader and Nate Hopper a creative executive. 
</P>
